Spark Deployment Modes ( where the Spark driver runs )   
    Client Mode
        Driver location: Runs on the machine submitting the Spark job (client).
        Executors: Run on cluster nodes.
        Use case: Interactive jobs (notebooks, Spark shell).
        Pros: Immediate feedback for users, easy debugging.
        Cons: If client machine fails, the job fails.

        spark-submit --master yarn --deploy-mode client app.py


    Cluster Mode
        Driver location: Runs on a cluster node.
        Executors: Run on other cluster nodes.
        Use case: Batch jobs, production pipelines, long-running jobs.
        Pros: Fault-tolerant, client machine not needed after submission.
        Cons: Harder to debug; driver logs are on cluster node

        spark-submit --master yarn --deploy-mode cluster app.py

        spark = SparkSession.builder \
                    .appName("ClusterModeExample") \
                    .master("yarn") \
                    .config("spark.submit.deployMode", "cluster") \
                    .getOrCreate()



    Local Mode    
        Driver & Executors: Both run on the same machine.
        Use case: Development, testing, and debugging small datasets.
        Pros: Easy setup, fast startup, easy to debug.
        Cons: Not scalable, limited by local machine resources.

        Master URL examples:
            local → single-threaded
            local[4] → 4 threads
            local[*] → all available cores    

        from pyspark.sql import SparkSession

        spark = SparkSession.builder \
            .appName("LocalExample") \
            .master("local[*]") \
            .getOrCreate()



